### Closures — Event Emitter Pattern

A more sophisticated real-world use of closures: building a typed event emitter where both the event registry and listener lists are private.

```javascript
function createEventEmitter() {
  // Both 'listeners' and all its contents are private to this closure
  const listeners = {};

  return {
    on(event, fn) {
      if (!listeners[event]) listeners[event] = [];
      listeners[event].push(fn);
      // Return unsubscribe function — itself a closure over 'event' and 'fn'
      return () => this.off(event, fn);
    },
    off(event, fn) {
      if (!listeners[event]) return;
      listeners[event] = listeners[event].filter(f => f !== fn);
    },
    emit(event, ...args) {
      if (!listeners[event]) return;
      listeners[event].forEach(fn => fn(...args));
    },
    once(event, fn) {
      const wrapper = (...args) => {
        fn(...args);
        this.off(event, wrapper); // removes itself after first call
      };
      this.on(event, wrapper);
    }
  };
}

const emitter = createEventEmitter();

const unsubscribe = emitter.on('data', (payload) => {
  console.log('received:', payload);
});

emitter.once('connect', () => {
  console.log('connected — fires only once');
});

emitter.emit('data', { id: 1, value: 42 }); // 'received: { id: 1, value: 42 }'
emitter.emit('connect'); // 'connected — fires only once'
emitter.emit('connect'); // nothing — listener was removed

unsubscribe(); // stop listening to 'data'
emitter.emit('data', { id: 2 }); // nothing — unsubscribed

// 'listeners' is inaccessible from outside — true privacy
console.log(emitter.listeners); // undefined
```

**Common interview trap:** The `once` method creates a **wrapper closure** that references both the original `fn` and uses `this.off` to remove itself. The key insight: each call to `on` can return a different unsubscribe function because each call creates its own closure — not the same reference. If you passed `fn` directly to `off`, `once` would fail because `off` looks for the `wrapper` function, not `fn`.

