### async/await — Debugging, Stack Traces, and Top-Level Await

```javascript
// --- Stack trace difference ---
// Promise chain: stack trace is often unhelpful
function fetchData() {
  return fetch('/api')
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(data => {
      if (!data.id) throw new Error('Missing id');
      return data;
    });
}
// Error stack: "Error: Missing id" at anonymous — hard to trace

// async/await: stack trace names the async function
async function fetchData2() {
  const r = await fetch('/api');
  const data = await r.json();
  if (!data.id) throw new Error('Missing id');
  return data;
}
// Error stack: "Error: Missing id" at fetchData2 — much more useful!

// --- Top-level await (ES2022, works in ES modules) ---
// import.meta available in modules
const config = await fetch('/config.json').then(r => r.json());
console.log(config.apiUrl); // works at module top level

// --- async IIFE for immediate invocation ---
(async () => {
  const result = await someAsyncOperation();
  console.log(result);
})();

// --- Pitfall: sequential vs concurrent ---
// These run sequentially (2 seconds total if each takes 1s)
async function sequential() {
  const a = await fetchA(); // waits for A
  const b = await fetchB(); // then waits for B
  return [a, b];
}

// These run concurrently (1 second total)
async function concurrent() {
  const [a, b] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB()]);
  return [a, b];
}

// This starts both but awaits sequentially — WRONG for concurrency
async function startedConcurrentlyAwaitedSequentially() {
  const promiseA = fetchA(); // started
  const promiseB = fetchB(); // started (not awaited yet)
  const a = await promiseA; // but awaited in order — still concurrent!
  const b = await promiseB;
  return [a, b];
}
// Actually runs concurrently — both promises are in flight before first await

// --- async function always returns a Promise ---
async function returnPrimitive() {
  return 42;
}
returnPrimitive().then(v => console.log(v)); // 42 — wrapped in Promise
console.log(returnPrimitive() instanceof Promise); // true
```

**Common interview trap:** Starting both promise-returning functions then `await`-ing sequentially IS concurrent execution (both fire immediately). The issue only arises when you `await` before starting the second operation. Many developers incorrectly believe `const a = await fetchA(); const b = await fetchB();` is the same as `await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB()])` — it is NOT. The first is sequential; `Promise.all` is truly parallel.

