### CommonJS vs ES Modules — The Dual Package Hazard and Migration

```javascript
// --- The live binding difference (critical for understanding) ---

// counter.mjs — ESM
export let count = 0;
export function increment() { count++; }

// consumer.mjs
import { count, increment } from './counter.mjs';
console.log(count); // 0
increment();
console.log(count); // 1 — ESM exports are LIVE BINDINGS

// counter.cjs — CJS
module.exports = { count: 0, increment() { this.count++; } };

// consumer.cjs
const { count, increment } = require('./counter.cjs');
console.log(count); // 0
increment.call(module.exports); // must call on the exports object
console.log(count); // still 0 — CJS copies the VALUE at require time!

// --- Interoperability ---
// ESM can import CJS (default import only):
import cjsModule from './legacy.cjs'; // gets module.exports as default
// import { named } from './legacy.cjs'; // may work in Node 20+, but not guaranteed

// CJS cannot synchronously require ESM:
// const esm = require('./modern.mjs'); // ERR_REQUIRE_ESM
// Must use dynamic import:
(async () => {
  const { add } = await import('./math.mjs'); // works
})();

// --- Dual package: publish for both ---
// package.json
// {
//   "exports": {
//     ".": {
//       "import": "./dist/index.mjs",
//       "require": "./dist/index.cjs"
//     }
//   }
// }
// Dual package hazard: if both versions end up loaded, two separate instances exist!
// State held in CJS version is NOT shared with ESM version

// --- When to use each ---
// Node.js CLI tools, legacy codebases: CJS (easier, no configuration)
// Modern web apps, bundled code, new packages: ESM (tree-shaking, live bindings)
// Node.js >= 22 supports ESM natively with .mjs or "type": "module" in package.json
```

**Common interview trap:** `import` at the top of a file is **hoisted** — all static imports are processed before any code runs. This means you can't have a static `import` inside an `if` block (SyntaxError). For conditional imports, use dynamic `import()` which returns a Promise. Also, circular dependencies in CJS return a **partially populated** object (whatever was exported before the cycle was reached), while ESM handles circular dependencies via live bindings (the binding exists but may be `undefined` until initialization completes).

