### Well-Known Symbols — Beyond Symbol.iterator

JavaScript has 13 built-in well-known symbols that hook into language semantics.

```javascript
// --- Symbol.toPrimitive: control type coercion ---
class Money {
  constructor(amount, currency) {
    this.amount = amount;
    this.currency = currency;
  }

  [Symbol.toPrimitive](hint) {
    if (hint === 'number') return this.amount;
    if (hint === 'string') return `${this.amount} ${this.currency}`;
    return this.amount; // 'default' hint (used by == and +)
  }
}

const price = new Money(42, 'USD');
console.log(+price);      // 42 (number hint)
console.log(`${price}`);  // '42 USD' (string hint)
console.log(price + 10);  // 52 (default hint → number)
console.log(price == 42); // true (default hint)

// --- Symbol.hasInstance: control instanceof ---
class EvenNumber {
  static [Symbol.hasInstance](value) {
    return typeof value === 'number' && value % 2 === 0;
  }
}

console.log(4 instanceof EvenNumber);  // true
console.log(3 instanceof EvenNumber);  // false
console.log(8 instanceof EvenNumber);  // true

// --- Symbol.toStringTag: control Object.prototype.toString ---
class ReadableStream {
  get [Symbol.toStringTag]() { return 'ReadableStream'; }
}

const stream = new ReadableStream();
console.log(Object.prototype.toString.call(stream)); // '[object ReadableStream]'
console.log(stream.toString()); // '[object ReadableStream]'

// --- Symbol.iterator on a class ---
class Range {
  constructor(start, end, step = 1) {
    this.start = start; this.end = end; this.step = step;
  }

  [Symbol.iterator]() {
    let current = this.start;
    const { end, step } = this;
    return {
      next() {
        if (current > end) return { value: undefined, done: true };
        const value = current;
        current += step;
        return { value, done: false };
      },
      [Symbol.iterator]() { return this; } // self-referential for re-use
    };
  }
}

const r = new Range(0, 10, 2);
console.log([...r]); // [0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10]
for (const n of r) process.stdout.write(n + ' '); // works multiple times
```

**Common interview trap:** `Symbol.toPrimitive` takes precedence over both `valueOf()` and `toString()`. When coercion occurs, JavaScript checks for `Symbol.toPrimitive` first. If not found, it falls back to `valueOf()` then `toString()`. Also, the three hints — `'number'`, `'string'`, `'default'` — are distinct: `+obj` uses `'default'`, not `'number'`; template literals use `'string'`; arithmetic operators use `'number'`.

